Between 1911 and 1937, he was the frequent accompanist to the Spanish violinist Manuel Quiroga on his international tours.
On 8 June 1937, he had just said goodbye to Quiroga after a concert in New York when the violinist was hit by a truck in Times Square, which led to the premature end of his career.

After a court battle of several months, Iturbi and his former son-in-law ultimately resolved their differences, and the girls remained with their father.
Iturbi's companion for many years was Marion Seabury, his secretary, who survived him and founded the José Iturbi Foundation after his death.
